<TEXT>
fire raged through a subway tunnel under 
construction near downtown friday collapsing a section near the 
hollywood freeway and snarling traffic when the thoroughfare was 
shut for fear it might also fall 
commuters were thrown into chaos and firefighters and engineers 
reported damage to the metro rail tunnel running under the freeway 
one of the principal routes linking northern and southern 
california 
current information has part of the tunnel collapsed due to 
failure of the metal rings binding the tunnel together said city 
chief administrative officer richard b dixon 
by late afternoon the blaze was confined and contained but 
not out fire spokesman greg acevedo said 
the tunnel is 750 feet long the fire is in 450 feet of it 
he said 
about 150 firefighters remained on site but were unable to get 
far into the tunnel because of the intense heat he said 
fire department estimates variously put the collapsed section at 
80 or 140 feet by 20 feet a california department of 
transportation spokeswoman said the collapsed section was at least 
100 feet and included a segment under the freeway 
were quite concerned about the integrity of the freeway 
said deputy fire chief craig drummond 
the fires cause was unknown and not likely to be known until it 
was out 
there was no estimate of when the fire would be controlled and 
predictions of when the freeway would be reopened stretched as long 
as monday morning 
as big a headache as it is we want to be safe said margie 
tiritilli a spokeswoman for caltrans we want to make sure that 
the structure will not collapse and were just not certain 
underneath with that tunnel 
the 13 billion 4mile subway project was scheduled to open 
sometime in 1993 officials of the southern california rapid 
transit district werent sure how the fire would affect the 
timetable 
smoke poured out of tunnel vents and the odor permeated downtown 
it started getting to me it was just disgusting said jeff 
singer who got to work at the district attorneys office after 
being stuck in traffic almost an hour it was just starting to 
make me nauseous 
firefighters poured water into the tunnel during the first hours 
and then began considering whether to smother it with foam or pump 
in an inert gas such as nitrogen to displace the oxygen that 
allowed the fire to burn 
two minor injuries to firefighters were reported six cleanup 
crew workers in one of two underground tubes smelled smoke in the 
adjacent tunnel and escaped unharmed 
the top of the tunnel is 18 feet underground the tunnel is 19 
feet in diameter 
the hollywood freeway us 101 is a main artery linking 
downtown to hollywood and the san fernando valley suburbs traffic 
from the valley was suprisingly light some commuters reported but 
freeways such as the santa ana san bernardino and glendale were 
snarled as they tied into the downtown grid surface streets also 
backed up 
it was a mess said elizabeth munnerlyn a court secretary 
who got to work two hours late 
some mail will not be delivered today they could not get into 
some areas because of safety reasons said larry dozier of the 
postal service the downtown post office on los angeles street is 
just blocks from the fire 
</TEXT>
