<TEXT>
when the organization of african 
unity was born 27 years ago many nations on the continent were 
ruled by european powers today the countries are selfruled but 
unity peace and prosperity still elude them 
african heads of state and government who gathered this week for 
the oaus 26th summit pointed to the democratic movements that have 
swept eastern europe and expressed hopes for political reform on 
their own continent 
we recommit ourselves to the full democratization of our 
societies and to the consolidation of democratic institutions in 
our countries taking into account the realities of each of our 
countries views the leaders said in a communique wednesday at 
the end of their threeday gathering in the ethiopian capital of 
addis ababa 
but in the cases of some african leaders the pledge to 
democratize seemed like little more than lip service 
most of africas 550 million people are governed by dictators or 
live in oneparty states popular upheavals and civil wars are 
convulsing the continent and force is the most common response by 
african governments 
some african leaders were feeling too beleaguered to attend the 
oau summit 
liberian president samuel doe under siege in monrovia from 
rebels seeking to seize control did not attend the conference 
president kenneth kaunda of zambia still recovering from riots 
against food price hikes that left 26 people dead last month 
stayed away for the first time since he led his country to 
independence in 1964 
and kenyan president daniel arap moi cut short his visit and 
flew home on the first day after a weekend of rioting sparked by 
demands for a multiparty democracy in his oneparty state 
the absent leaders might have been mindful that leaving their 
own capitals could give their opponents an opening to act 
yakubu gowan of nigeria was toppled in a 1975 coup while he was 
attending an oau summit and milton obote of uganda was overthrown 
during the 1971 british commonwealth summit in singapore 
the oaus original charter pledged action to improve the living 
standards of all africans to defend sovereignity territorial 
integrity and independence and to rid the continent of all traces 
of colonialism 
the colonial powers have departed but other dreams remained 
unfulfilled 
living standards have plunged and wars rage in liberia uganda 
angola ethiopia somalia and sudan 
a common market proposed in 1980 has yet to be formed a move to 
militarily confront whiteruled south africa never materialized 
and leaders are still striving for continental unity 
of the 30 heads of state who signed the oau charter on may 25 
1963 only seven were still in power in 1980 of the others seven 
were assassinated by their own troops 17 were ousted in coups two 
died of natural causes and one bowed out of office 
some leaders conceded they felt left out of the sweeping changes 
elsewhere in the world 
it was we africans who raised high the banner of unity well 
before many regions of the world ethiopian president mengistu 
haile mairam told this weeks gathering 
but viewed against the current trend of rapid changes in the 
international scene and the movement towards harmony and unity 
among countries in various regions of the world the pace of 
progress we are making to achieve continental unity has indeed been 
very slow he said 
julius nyerere former president of tanzania lamented that 
african leaders had not followed northern industrialized nations in 
burying differences in order to improve trade and their economies 
one bright spot at the summit was the presence of nelson 
mandela the black south african nationalist leader who was in 
prison when the oau was created for many of those present 
mandelas release in february was symbolic of moves toward reform 
in south africa 
but south africas system of racial segregation has at least 
provided a rallying point for the oau states if apartheid is 
eventually dismantled some observers said the oau might not find 
much else to agree on 
