<TEXT>
many cancer patients in the united states are 
increasingly likely to survive but for about 30000 hit by throat 
and mouth cancer every year the chances are roughly 5050 and not 
getting any better 
oral and pharynx cancers killed 9742 americans in 1987 the 
latest year for which statistics are available the national 
centers for disease control reported thursday 
that fatality rate 36 deaths per 100000 people is 
unchanged from 1973 said cdc dental health specialist linda 
crossett 
but the survival rate hasnt changed much since then either the 
atlantabased disease center said 
only 52 percent of oral cancer patients survive five years or 
more thats in contrast to the survival rates for breast prostate 
and colorectal cancers which are improving officials said 
survival rates are lowest for blacks and getting worse 
statistics for 1981 through 1986 showed that just 31 percent of 
black patients survived oral cancer compared with 35 percent in 
197476 
for white patients the survival rates have remained more 
constant 53 percent from 1981 through 1986 down from 55 percent 
during 197476 
were not making a lot of progress crossett said adding 
that about 30000 new cases a year are diagnosed in the united 
states 
major risk factors for oral cancer include use of tobacco 
either smoked or smokeless and drinking 
the combined risks from tobacco and alcohol use appear to be 
substantially greater than those from tobacco or alcohol alone 
the cdc said in its weekly report 
the increased use of tobacco among women adolescents and 
children as compared to a decline in smoking overall is 
likely to elevate death rates for these cancers in the next several 
decades the report said 
another major reason for oral cancer deaths is the fact that 
there has not been any improvement in early detection crossett 
said most are only detected after theyve grown pretty 
large so advanced that its obvious 
dentists traditionally have been most likely to perform 
extensive oral exams but the cdc documented in 1986 that people at 
highest risk for oral cancer seek the services of a physician four 
times more often than a dentist 
and many people going to their physician may not get a 
thorough oral head and neck exam crossett said 
