while these estimates are preliminary and they will change 
the potential for harmful side effects is with us to stay he 
said 
an independent panel of scientists was scheduled to meet here 
today to begin the second phase of a fiveyear study they will try 
to determine individual radiation exposure and health risks for 
those who lived downwind from the 560squaremile site 
the first phase studied airborne radioactive iodine emissions 
from 1944 to 1947 and radioactive cooling water poured into the 
columbia river from 196467 
the fiveyear 15 million study is being paid for but not 
directed by the us department of energy which operates the 
reservation 
hanford was established late in world war ii as part of the 
manhattan project to build atomic bombs 
fuel rods irradiated in as many as nine nuclear reactors at the 
site were taken to several topsecret plants where plutonium and 
uranimum were extracted to fuel nuclear bombs 
the iodine and other radioactive materials was released into the 
air through unfiltered stacks officials said 
a few infants were hit hardest with doses as high as 2900 rad 
over three years one rad is the amount of radiation a body organ 
would absorb from about a dozen chest xrays 
the panel concluded that most people living near the hanford 
site from 1944 to 1947 were exposed to low doses of radiation the 
study covered 270000 people living in 10 washington and oregon 
counties 
in releasing the first phase report john till a south carolina 
scientist and nuclear consultant cautioned that the results should 
not be used to make health risk estimates 
but as many as 13500 people or 5 percent of the population 
may have received doses of more than 33 rad in milk after cows 
grazed in contaminated pastures he said 
about 1400 infants and children living in the area received 15 
to 650 rad with only a small number suffering the 2900rad doses 
till said 
when it concentrates in the thyroid gland radioactive 
iodine131 can cause cancer and other diseases 
scientists hope that within a year they will be able to tell 
people who lived in the area what their highest potential radiation 
doses likely were 
such information would greatly help doctors treat affected 
residents dr george laramore professor of radiological oncology 
at the university of washington school of medicine in seattle 
bailie led an impromptu press conference of downwind residents 
angered by the report that came decades after radiation was 
routinely released in the rural agricultural area 
