southeast asian countries burdened by thousands of vietnamese 
who fled their communist homeland have threatened to forcibly 
repatriate refugees unless the united states and other countries 
help resettle them 
fiftynine refugees are awaiting authorization from vietnam to 
return while another 130 have indicated they want to go back the 
un statement said 
in the departures from thailand an official of the un high 
commissioner for refugees said 113 refugees from the phanat nikhom 
refugee camp had volunteered to return to vietnam and would be 
interviewed by vietnamese immigration officials in thailand early 
next week 
the official who spoke on condition of anonymity said he 
expected the refugees would return to vietnam within one or two 
months 
there are now some 14000 vietnamese refugees in thailand less 
than 2000 are currently eligible for thirdcountry resettlement 
all vietnamese who arrived in thailand after march 14 1989 must 
be screened to determine their eligibility for resettlement most 
of the vietnamese refugees now in thailand arrived after that 
cutoff date 
the group of 113 had not yet been screened the official said 
it appeared they were returning due to the lengthy screening 
process and because they were pessimistic about the prospect for 
eventual resettlement another relief official said 
the un official said the number of vietnamese arriving in 
thailand had increased in the first five months of this year to an 
average of about 1000 he said it appeared the vietnamese now 
perceived thailand to be more receptive to them than countries 
malaysia and hong kong 
there are about 17500 vietnamese refugees in malaysian camps 
of these 14000 arrived after the march 1989 cutoff date 
vietnamese began fleeing their homeland after the communist 
victory over usbacked forces in south vietnam in 1975 
</TEXT>
