<TEXT>
south korea today denied allegations 
in an amnesty international report that said the country holds 
hundreds of political prisoners and has tortured some of them 
the justice ministry said in a statement that since president 
roh taewoo took office in 1988 no individual has been punished 
simply for harboring certain political views 
it is regrettable that without giving any evidence or 
criteria amnesty international defined some of those in prison 
as prisoners of conscience and demanded their release the 
statement said 
in its annual report released wednesday amnesty international 
charged that south korea holds about 900 political prisoners and 
some have been tortured 
in south korea there are no prisoners of conscience as 
referred to by the international amnesty report those who remain 
in prison have either violated laws or endangered the very safety 
of our nation the statement said 
it said that many of those defined as prisoners of 
conscience by the londonbased human rights monitoring group are 
spies sent by north korea it said the communist nation poses a 
serious threat to south koreas security 
the two koreas have been bitter rivals since the division of the 
korean peninsula in 1945 
addressing the issue of torture the statement said two suspects 
died last year in police custody but that they were isolated cases 
two policemen involved in torturing the prisoners were arrested and 
put on trial it said 
in its annual world survey of human rights amnesty also said 
thousands of people were imprisoned tortured and killed last year 
by governments seeking to suppress conflicts arising from ethnic 
tensions or nationalist yearnings 
</TEXT>
