<TEXT>
scores of east german factories agreed friday 
to raise wages and preserve jobs for 350000 metalworkers but said 
the labor contract may actually speed the collapse of some plants 
the oneyear pact was reached after a series of strikes by 
hundreds of thousands of metalworkers around berlin it is the 
biggest labor agreement since east germany became a free market on 
july 1 
the contract at least temporarily ends one of many 
confrontations between former government enterprises facing new 
western competition and workers demanding better pay to cope with 
suddenly higher food prices 
but while one labor dispute was settled another arose almost 
immediately about 60000 retail industry workers held 
demonstrations in a halfdozen cities friday to protest plans to 
dissolve the governmentrun retail chains 
east germany meanwhile said it is facing a huge drop in income 
because of declining production and would need more money from west 
germany 
finance minister walter romberg told parliament that east 
germany would have nearly 387 billion in expenditures through the 
second half of this year but only 175 billion in income 
east germany merged its economy with west germanys on july 1 in 
a prelude to the full unification expected later this year 
it is now in the early stages of converting its moribund 
centrally planned economy to a market economy prices have risen 
dramatically and east german companies already are feeling the 
effects of western competition 
many east german factories are expected to fail causing wide 
unemployment in the coming months workers in several industries 
have staged warning strikes to press their demands for job 
protection and better wages 
the metalworkers contract ends a bitter confrontation 
the contract was negotiated by the powerful west german labor 
union ig metall and its east german affiliate and covers 350000 
workers at 164 factories in an area around berlin 
management said the pact may hasten the closing of enterprises 
already struggling to meet their payrolls 
this extensive compromise package is not economically 
justifiable lothar heinzmann head of the employers group said 
in a statement carried by the east german news agency adn 
he called it an advance payment for an uncertain future 
in a statement the union said the agreement keeps the burden of 
moving to a free market from being placed fully on the workers 
the contract is expected to set a pattern for other labor 
agreements currently being negotiated 
it must be feared that factories will close because of this 
contract said christoph borchelt spokesman for the employer 
association the association of metal and electronics industries of 
berlin and brandenburg 
the agreement raises the annual monthly salary of 666 to 850 
through october then to 880 through april 1 when the wage 
portion of the contract expires 
the jobguarantee section runs through june 1991 after which 
workers can be laid off 
the contract also increases the factories participation in a 
government program aimed at heading off layoffs 
under the program financed largely by west germany workers 
targeted for layoffs receive 63 percent of their salaries while 
remaining in the plants where they receive training for other jobs 
the contract will increase factory participation in the program 
raising the salaries of workers targeted by layoffs to 85 percent 
of their former wages 
about 220000 east german workers nationwide are in such 
programs and another 240000 are expected to be added shortly the 
government said about 162000 workers are unemployed 
negotiations are continuing in other parts of metalworking and 
electronics industries a sector that employs 16 million of the 
nations 8 million workers 
