<TEXT>
the gunslinger of the old west may be 
poised for a comeback in mississippi because of a loophole in a 
new gun law 
on july 1 the states new gun permit law went into effect and 
to the chagrin of the governor lawmakers and law enforcement 
officials it allows most mississippians to tote concealed handguns 
almost anywhere including sports events bars and even the state 
capitol 
an 11thhour attempt to fix the flawed legislation failed in a 
special legislative session last month and law enforcement 
officials fear its looseness will allow the wrong people to be 
armed and in the wrong places 
its the law and weve got to live with it said sharkey 
county sheriff joe ford president of the mississippi sheriffs 
association 
the law allows mississippians over age 21 willing to pay 100 
for a threeyear permit to carry a concealed weapon the only 
exceptions are convicted felons fugitives drug and alcohol 
abusers the mentally incompetent illegal aliens those 
dishonorably discharged from the military those who renounce their 
citizenship or those who falsify permit applications 
applicants must undergo background checks be fingerprinted and 
photographed but the background check requirement is indicative of 
what critics say is the sloppiness of the law 
it says that applications are to be issued within 30 days but 
the state department of public safety says such checks with the fbi 
take about six weeks its also not clear when the 30day period is 
intended to start 
and law enforcement officials complain theres no provision for 
revoking the permits which are automatically renewable 
the law began as a state senate bill to allow judges to carry 
handguns but it evolved in the house into a bill to loosen up an 
old law that defined a weapon as concealed if any part of it was 
not open to view 
lawmakers have since admitted they made a mistake but they 
failed to pass a cleanup bill at last months special session 
unless gov ray mabus calls a special session for which there 
are no plans the law stays on the books until the legislature can 
act when it meets in regular session in early january 
the mississippi rifle and pistol association an affliate of the 
national rifle association lobbied for the passage of the law but 
with the understanding that the glitches would be ironed out said 
group president david hawkins 
hawkins said he was disappointed that the cleanup bill was not 
passed it was a very good compromise a bill we all liked and 
something we could live with thats what we wanted passed he 
said 
state and law enforcement officials in mississippi are still 
assessing what has happened and what can be done said cliff 
treyens a spokesman for mabus 
officials hope to have a solution by the end of the month 
possibly before the first of the permits are issued 
applications are accepted only on wednesday beginning with this 
week on the first day 426 people sought permits 
in 1987 florida also had to fix a flaw in a new concealed 
weapons law after lawmakers inadvertently repealed a provision that 
prohibited people from carrying firearms openly in public 
once the glitch was discovered lawmakers came back into session 
to repeal it and are now satisified with the amended law said 
robin hassler staff director of the florida house of 
representativess committee on criminal justice 
lawmakers say mississippis law once it is amended will be 
similar to floridas 
