<TEXT>
lawmakers friday voted to sell off 
polands state industries a major step in the solidarityled 
governments 7monthold program of radical economic reforms 
designed to build a market economy 
the author of those reforms deputy prime minister leszek 
balcerowicz described the legislation as the most fundamental 
bill ever passed by the polish parliament 
the government owns 80 percent of industry in poland including 
steel mills coal mines and factories none of the 7600 state 
enterprises would be offlimits to privatization officials said 
all citizens will be given privatization bonds that can be 
redeemed for company stocks allowing the estimated 65 percent of 
polish families with no savings to become shareholders 
the sejm or the lower house of parliament passed the 
legislation 3282 with 39 abstentions the vote came one day after 
the longdelayed bill reached the floor 
a separate bill creating a ministry to oversee the changes 
passed 2660 with 22 abstentions 
the legislation must still be ratified by the senate on july 19 
but with 99 of 100 senators elected from the noncommunist 
solidarity movement it was not expected to encounter any 
difficulty 
this is a foundation of the new economic system in poland 
balcerowicz said after the vote 
the finance ministry official in charge of privatization 
krzysztof lis said there would be problems putting the bill into 
practice such as assembling the new ministry and creating a stock 
market 
but wide consensus has been created for privatization and 
this is the most important thing lis said 
before introducing the vote on thursday balcerowicz said the 
ownership changes must be completed more quickly than in any 
country that has attempted it before us 
companies in the best financial shape would be sold first those 
judged unsalvageable will be liquidated and their assets sold off 
still officials estimated that only a dozen major factories 
would be privatized in the first year and even after three years 
fewer than half would be in private hands 
meanwhile selling or leasing state stores boutiques 
restaurants and services to individuals socalled small 
privatization is already under way and is expected to be 
completed by late 1991 
hungary and czechoslovakia are moving toward selling off their 
state industries 
in hungary the new centrist government has sold some 
enterprises but is taking a cautious approach hoping to minimize 
the negative consequences such as unemployment and higher prices 
in czechoslovakia the government intends to issue coupons this 
fall that would allow workers to buy their own companies the main 
privatization laws are expected next year 
poland whose communist regime was replaced by the solidarity 
government of prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki in august in 
january embarked on a radical economic reform program the first 
goal was to stabilize runaway inflation 
the program whittled inflation down to 34 percent in june 
compared with 600 percent to 1000 percent inflation in 1989 but 
the social cost has been high real incomes have dropped by 30 
percent 
but the privatization measure was stalled for months because of 
disputes over how to proceed many people feared privatization 
would benefit only foreign investors or the former communist elite 
who alone would have capital to buy state property 
but the government promised to issue all citizens 
privatization bonds which can be used toward the purchase of 
stateowned property 
it also promised citizens would be allowed to buy shares on an 
installment basis and in some cases on favorable credit terms 
in this way the idea of citizens stock ownership will be put 
into practice balcerowicz said 
in a nod to workers who under communist rule came to think of 
factories as their property employees can buy up to 20 percent of 
shares in their own companies on preferential terms 
foreign investment will be at the discretion of the minister 
responsible for privatization officials said 
the first step in the process will be to convert all stateowned 
enterprises into jointstock companies owned in full by the state 
treasury they said 
