<TEXT>
the head of nasas investigation of the hubble 
space telescopes blurred vision said friday it may take more than 
six months to pinpoint the error but that the probe should reveal 
what went wrong and who was responsible 
dr lew allen chairman of the nasa review panel told a house 
panel the results of the investigation could prove very 
embarrassing to those responsible for the flaw 
we are confident we have the ability to find the error and 
determine responsibility he said 
allen making his first congressional appearance since the probe 
began testified before the house committee on science space and 
technology 
the most likely problem allen said is an error in the 
curvature of the telescopes primary 94inch mirror that makes it 
impossible to properly focus the 15 billion observatory 
the margin of error is microscopic to the human eye but enough 
to make the telescopes vision no better than quality observatories 
on the ground the mistake makes it impossible to focus light from 
all parts of the mirror onto one point 
dr lennard a fisk a nasa associate administrator said the 
focus problem will be corrected for the main hubble camera in 1993 
when a replacement camera is flown up to the telescope by the space 
shuttle and spacewalking astronauts switch instruments 
but that mission will correct the focus for only one of the five 
instruments on board hubble other corrections will have to wait 
until 1996 and later 
the error is very large said fisk therefore some simple 
lowcost norisk test could have been done that could have 
detected the flaw 
asked why such tests before the telescope was assemble were not 
performed fisk said were asking those same questions 
allen said the instrument used to measure the mirrors when they 
were constructed nearly a decade ago a null corrector has been 
untouched since it was used and was impounded by the review 
panel 
if there was an error in the corrector it would cause the 
primary mirror to be configured wrong he said 
committee chairman robert a roe dnj said allens probe 
could be too narrow and not lead to broad changes in the way nasa 
manages complicated programs and tests complex equipment 
but fisk the chief scientist for the national aeronautics and 
space administration said if we stop at the findings of dr 
allens panel then we will not have done our job we wont stop at 
that 
fisk said he would determine if any management changes should be 
made and would agree to having another panel of outside experts 
examine the agencys management system but only after allens 
review panel concluded its work 
allen said the null corrector that measured the primary mirror 
also was used to measure a 60inch demonstration mirror for the 
telescope project that allows investigators to test the measuring 
instrument to see whether the corrector caused the problem 
but all of these tests will be timeconsuming allen said and 
he told the committee the probe will take perhaps six months or 
more 
we know the most likely outcome from our investigation he 
said will be findings that are very embarrassing to someone or 
some group 
members peppered fisk with questions on why the mirrors werent 
tested after the entire telescope was built 
although fisk cited technical reasons for the decision nasa 
officials had said in earlier statements that such testing would 
have required up to 300 million and the construction of a special 
facility 
the testing fisk said would have been extremely complicated 
it was questionable whether it would yield the information we 
wanted and it ran serious risk of contaminating the mirrors for 
measuring ultra violet rays a function that was not affected by 
the focus flaw 
