<DOCNO> AP900713-0119 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a federal appeals court ordered a district 
judge on friday to reconsider his denial of a request by nynex 
corp that it be allowed to distribute telecommunications equipment 
to other companies 
the ruling by a threejudge panel of the us court of appeals 
for the district of columbia marks another turning point in the 
battle by the seven regional bell telephone companies to escape 
restrictions placed on them in the 1984 breakup of the old bell 
system 
the appeals court said us district judge harold greene who 
continues to oversee the consent decree that effected the bell 
breakup failed to properly address the competitive issues raised 
by new yorkbased nynexs possible entry into the 
telecommunications distribution business 
the 1982 consent decree under which nynex and the other regional 
bell companies were created prohibited them from engaging in the 
longdistance equipment manufacturing and distribution businesses 
among other restrictions 
nynex in 1985 asked greene for a waiver to allow its wholly 
owned purchasing unit nynex materiel enterprises co to 
distribute telecommunications products to customers unaffiliated 
with nynex greene denied the request 
nynex appealed to the higher court american telephone amp 
telegraph co along with a host of other telecommunications 
equipment manufacturers filed briefs with the appeals court 
arguing against nynex 
the appeals court friday left little doubt that it looked 
favorably on nynexs waiver request 
under our reading of the decree which differed in some 
important particulars from that of the district court it may well 
be that nynex is entitled to the relief it seeks in this case 
circuit judge laurence h silberman wrote 
the basis of the consent decree restrictions is the fear that 
the bell companies may use their positions as monopoly local phone 
service providers to impede competition or that they may make their 
captive local phone customers foot the bill for new ventures 
the appeals court said it saw significant merit in nynexs 
argument that since thousands of companies are competing in the 
telecommunications distribution market that its entry therefore 
would be competitively benign 
nynex this year has been hit with a federal indictment for 
allegedly violating the consent decrees restrictions on providing 
computerized information services the federal communications 
commission also fined nynex a record 14 million for allegedly 
overcharging customers through its materiel enterprises division 
nynex has denied any wrongdoing 
the wall street journal reported this week that nynex also is 
being investigated for allegations that suppliers for nynexs new 
york telephone helped pay for bawdy parties and prostitutes at 
annual conventions involving materiel enterprises employees 
greene previously has lifted some of the restrictions on the 
bells provision of information services and nontelecommunications 
products and services but he has refused to ease other 
lineofbusiness restrictions 
the bell companies currently are waging an intense campaign in 
congress to get some of the remaining restrictions eliminated 
the senate could vote on lifting the manufacturing restrictions 
this year 
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

