<TEXT>
the house appropriations committee on friday 
approved 504 billion for agriculture spending in fiscal 1991 but 
angered house agriculture committee leaders by virtually 
eliminating crop insurance 
rep glenn english dokla whose agriculture subcommittee has 
been working on improvements to the crop insurance program said an 
amendment to restore funding would be offered during full house 
debate if the program is not reinstated sooner 
abolishing the program while major improvements are under 
consideration creates a situation whereby those improvements cannot 
be put into effect in an orderly manner agriculture committee 
chairman kika de la garza said in a letter to appropriations 
chairman jamie whitten 
the letter also was signed by english rep edward madigan 
rill and rep thomas coleman rmo 
madigan is ranking republican on the full agriculture committee 
and coleman the ranking gop member on englishs subcommittee 
meanwhile congressional leaders said the senate expects to 
start debate next week on the 1990 farm bill with budget 
constraints as the guiding force in determining the agriculture 
policy for the next five years 
aside from the factor of time the bottom line for acceptance 
and passage of this legislation must be the budget said senate 
republican leader bob dole in a news release 
the house version of the farm bill will be taken up next week by 
the house rules committee which will decide on the rules for 
debating the measure on the house floor 
the appropriations measure the house panel approved friday 
provides funding for all agriculture department agencies except the 
forest service it includes funds for the food and drug 
administration and the commodity futures trading commission and 
puts limits on funds for the farm credit administration and the 
farm credit system assistance board 
the overall appropriation for the fiscal year beginning oct 1 
is 5 billion greater than fiscal 1990 
the boost is reflected in higher allocations for administrative 
salaries payments to landgrant colleges research grants food 
safety and inspection marketing services and rural development 
the popular food program for poor pregnant and nursing mothers 
and their infants known as wic was allocated 235 billion an 
increase of 195 million from this year and 109 million more than 
the bush administration requested 
whitten dmiss a longtime opponent of crop insurance favors 
a system through which the government appropriates money to pay 
farmers each time there is a substantial crop loss 
the measure passed by whittens committee allows for 262 
million to be spent next year on crop insurance administrative 
phaseout costs and to make payments on any policies sold before 
oct 1 
the bush administration which also wants the program abolished 
has said 601 million would be needed in 1991 to operate crop 
insurance at its current level spending for 1990 has been 400 
million 
a straightout disaster program would be as expensive 
english said 
only about 40 percent of eligible farmers buy crop insurance 
farmers say they avoid the program because the premiums are too 
high yields are inadequate or because the price forecasting for 
certain crops by the insurance companies is inaccurate 
farmers may buy insurance from either the government or private 
companies thirty percent of all costs are paid by the federal 
government 
