an aide to attorney general dick thornburgh 
confirmed friday that his security clearance was revoked for 
failing to provide full background information for 18 months 
associate deputy attorney general barry h stern who turned in 
his resignation this week said he ignored repeated requests for 
what he termed minor information 
stern also confirmed that until last week he hadnt signed an 
oath that he had given truthful answers on the background 
questionnaire he filed last year 
if i didnt sign it it was a pure oversight said stern 
adding that signed the oath after belatedly providing the 
information sought by security officials he also said he signed a 
statement last year authorizing the fbi to conduct a background 
investigation 
stern a 43yearold lawyer said his security clearance was 
revoked last month because he had failed to provide information 
that involved addresses of some references and some job history 
information 
stern who oversaw the justice departments program for seizing 
the assets of drug dealers organized crime figures and other 
convicted criminals said his duties did not require him to have 
access to classified information 
the revocation of sterns security clearance is the latest 
personnel problem for thornburgh who reassigned two of his closest 
aides after it was disclosed they showed deception on lie 
detector tests during an fbi investigation of an unauthorized news 
leak 
the may reassignments of chief of staff robert s ross jr and 
press spokesman david runkel were portrayed by officials as part of 
an effort to dispel the perception that thornburgh was surrounded 
by political cronies 
stern is one of a group of aides to the attorney general who 
served under thornburgh when he was governor of pennsylvania he 
will join a philadelphiaarea publishing company lrp press 
stern received a temporary security clearance when he joined the 
justice department in september 1988 while the fbi completed a 
background check 
such temporary clearances usually lasting 14 months allow top 
officials to function in sensitive positions pending final approval 
of permanent access to classified information officials said 
a justice department official familiar with the case said 
sterns delay in filing the information was unprecedented and 
angered department security officials aides in sterns position 
normally file the requested information within several weeks of 
taking office so the fbi can begin its work 
the justice departments security office asked stern in november 
to provide several answers to questions that he had not completed 
including the addresses of references 
stern said he put off returning the form with the completed 
answers over the christmas holidays and continued to procrastinate 
for six months despite intermittent requests 
