<TEXT>
congressional talks on a final clean air bill 
began friday as a white house aide said the president remains 
strongly opposed to giving financial aid to workers who lose jobs 
because of tougher pollution requirements 
the housesenate negotiations over the first strengthening of 
federal air pollution laws in 13 years are expected to take weeks 
as numerous differences in the complex house and senate bills are 
worked out 
rep john dingell dmich head of the house delegation to the 
talks made clear that he will not be rushed we have an enormous 
amount of work ahead of us he said 
dingell rejected pleas by senators at the hourlong session for 
a quick response to two initial senate proposals on two relatively 
obscure parts of the legislation 
sen max baucus dmont conference chairman said we have to 
work quickly if a compromise bill is to be completed before 
congress adjourns in early october 
no date was set for the next session of the house and senate 
conferees 
bills passed last spring by wide margins in both the house and 
senate call for tougher pollution controls on factories 
automobiles and electric power plants to reduce urban smog toxic 
industrial releases and acid rain by the end of the decade 
but scores of differences remain between the two bills 
a major issue is job protection for workers who lose jobs 
because of tougher pollution controls the house bill contains a 
threeyear 250 million assistance program for such workers but 
the senate version does not 
roger porter president bushs chief domestic policy adviser 
who will sit in on the talks said the administration remains 
fundamentally opposed to a jobloss assistance provision he 
said he would recommend the president veto the bill if it contains 
such aid 
supporters of the assistance contend bush would be hard pressed 
to scuttle the massive package solely because it provides money for 
the unemployed they argue that the 250 million cost of the 
program is relatively small over three years 
but administration officials have argued there is no way to 
control the costs of mandated assistance it sets a precedent 
that were uncomfortable with said porter 
although no substantive agreements were reached in the first 
negotiating session senate majority leader george mitchell 
dmaine said he remained hopeful and certain a compromise 
clean air bill can be worked out before congress is scheduled to 
adjourn in october 
