<TEXT>
university of florida researchers 
announced friday the first clinical trials of a drug they hope will 
prevent juvenile diabetes the most deadly strain of the disease 
the study is being led by diabetes specialists at the 
universitys health science center it involves giving daily doses 
of an immunosuppressant drug called imuran to people likely to be 
afflicted 
also known as type 1 or insulindependent diabetes juvenile 
diabetes affects 1 million people and kills 300000 americans each 
year said dr noel maclaren a uf pathologist 
the medical centers involved in the study will offer free 
screening to close relatives of people who have type 1 diabetes 
the national institutes of health granted 35 million to pay 
for the screening of about 10000 people while about 80 who have 
indications of diabetes would receive the new drug 
besides the university of florida participating centers include 
the joslin diabetes center at harvard medical school the barbara 
davis foundation and denver childrens hospital in denver and the 
university of washington in seattle 
the study is the result of research by maclaren and mark 
atkinson who discovered antibodies that precede the onset of 
juvenile diabetes 
in the june issue of the british medical journal lancet 
atkinson reported that an antibody he isolated can be detected up 
to seven years before symptoms of diabetes appear 
peggy polopolus of gainesville who has been taking the drug 
since 1984 has not developed diabetes despite having type 1 
antibodies 
were convinced the medication has prevented the disease 
said dr william riley who is directing the nationwide clinical 
trials 
the drug keeps the bodys immune system from destroying cells in 
the pancreas while it produces insulin a hormone essential to the 
bodys storage and use of sugars for energy riley said 
several patients who received imuran after being diagnosed with 
type 1 diabetes were able to stay off insulin for up to two years 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

