<TEXT>
the mayors of moscow and leningrad joined boris n 
yeltsin in quitting the communist party on friday putting the 
countrys two largest cities as well as its heartland republic in 
the hands of noncommunists 
it was not immediately clear how the resignations of the three 
leading reformers would affect their party organizations 
yeltsin began the exodus thursday and it gathered steam as the 
partys 28th congress drew to a close leaders of the democratic 
platform reform group said they would cap their departures by 
founding their own noncommunist party this fall 
mikhail s gorbachev the president and party leader said in an 
interview with cbs news that he had contempt for those who left 
the party 
he told the congress in a closing address that those who 
demand party repentance and the settling of accounts and brand the 
party as almost a criminal organization are simply out to remove it 
from the political scene and thereby deal a blow to the entire 
cause of revolutionary renewal 
moscow mayor gavriil popov and leningrad mayor anatoly sobchak 
said in a statement that the twoweek congress showed the 
complete inability of the party to offer the country a real program 
of transition to a new society 
popov an economist and sobchak a lawyer were elected this 
spring as reformminded candidates swept to power in local 
councils under their leadership the two city councils have been 
trying to break the control of local communist party organizations 
they have been active in the same reform circles of soviet 
politics as yeltsin 
moscow has about 9 million people and leningrad has 5 million 
they are by far the largest cities in the soviet union 
in his closing speech gorbachev said the party intended to 
drastically change its attitude to elected governing councils 
renounce attempts at substituting for them make every effort to 
assist them to stand up firmly on their feet and help deputies 
deal with problems involved in meeting vital popular needs 
yeltsin elected in may as president of the huge russian 
federation told the congress thursday he was quitting the party 
as president of the russian republic which has threequarters of 
the soviet unions territory and 52 percent of its people he must 
listen to all political parties and cannot obey only the communist 
party he said moscow and leningrad both lie within the russian 
republic 
the tass news agency quoted yeltsin as telling the russian 
parliament on friday that he made the decision with a heavy 
heart at the party congress delegates voted to strip him of his 
congress credentials 
an aide to popov who is traveling outside the soviet union 
read the statement from the moscow and leningrad mayors to 
reporters in moscows city hall 
aware of our responsibility before the people and history we 
have decided to withdraw from the communist party to help create a 
multiparty system and to have the possibility to more effectively 
lead the councils we head the statement said 
leaders of democratic platform made a declaration after 
yeltsins speech thursday that they also were quitting the party 
they said they would struggle to gain a fraction of the partys 
vast wealth in proportion to the percentage of the 18 million 
communist party members who join their new party 
at a news conference they said they would hold a founding 
congress for a new noncommunist party in october and that they 
believed many party members would follow them 
people see that the vicious circle has been broken said 
democratic platform leader vladimir lysenko of moscow 
gorbachev doesnt understand the size of the movement that 
started yesterday added stepan sulakhin of the siberian city of 
tomsk 
while democratic platform does not expect yeltsin to join 
boris yeltsin remains the leader of the entire democratic 
movement he said 
but sulakhin and other democratic platform leaders said it was 
too early to say exactly how many members of their own 
organization and of the party itself would join 
the new party also will have to work out its programs in the 
coming months they said 
our party will not be a communist party but it will not be a 
party of confrontation said vyacheslav shostakovsky who has 
been the rector of higher party school in moscow it will be a 
party of social progress 
shostakovsky said the new party would accept both market 
economics and private property in a new economic system but that 
the approach must be wellthought out 
shostakovsky estimated months ago that democratic platform had 
500000 to 600000 supporters among communist party members 
surveys by the group indicate that about 40 percent of the 18 
million members of the communist party are sympathizers 
