the nations top welfare official on 
friday commended a wisconsin experiment tying welfare benefits to 
school attendance but cautioned officials to resolve the programs 
administrative problems 
us health and social services secretary louis sullivan said 
his office would continue to monitor the learnfare program for 
improvement but had already found the programs goals quite 
laudable 
we feel that the data thus far merit continued investment in 
the program sullivan said at a news conference 
learnfare started in 1987 trims aid to families with dependent 
children benefits to families whose teenagers skip school it has 
been touted as an incentive for teenagers to continue their 
education and chances of employment but harshly criticized by 
welfare advocates 
the program was ordered suspended in milwaukee schools this week 
by us district judge terence evans who cited poor attendance 
records that have resulted in some families being wrongly penalized 
a lawsuit filed against the program said one family was evicted 
from its home and others had to turn to food pantries for food 
evans injunction applies only to the 3200 teenagers attending 
milwaukee public schools who have lost or are in danger of losing 
afdc benefits under learnfare the program continues in other parts 
of the state 
penalties under learnfare average about 100 a month for an 
average family receiving 517 a month in benefits 
sullivan who was in marshfield to dedicate a new 61 million 
research center at marshfield clinic said he was not concerned by 
the judges action 
obviously with any program that is new there are always a 
number of glitches or problems that might need to be addressed 
he said clearly the administrative issues must be addressed 
despite criticism that learnfare is a cruel and unsuccessful 
antitruancy tool the federal government in june approved 
wisconsins request to expand the program to include elementary 
children 
we have a number of problems that will be addressed by our 
society if we can improve our education approach sullivan said 
dropout rates are as high as 50 percent in some innercity 
schools he said 
