<TEXT>
after countless centuries of lumbering 
through fields and chewing cud bovines have moseyed into the art 
world 
the cow a pastoral fixture since ancient times and more 
recently the model for such kitsch items as tshirts and salt 
shakers is now the subject of a traveling art exhibit 
the cow in photograph and folktale displaying 39 
photographs of cows bulls and heifers opened last month at the 
new york state museum in downtown albany for the purpose of 
exploring the richness of bovine culture 
the show features photographs dating from the 19th century to 
today illustrating the cow in just about every imaginable 
circumstance and then some there are closeup cows cows in 
fields cows being milked cows in thistle and even a shot of a 
giant fiberglass cow 
for centuries the common image of the cow has inspired and 
intrigued artists working in all mediums in such simple and 
elegant views the beauty of the beast wrote caralee aber in the 
exhibits program notes 
aber put the show together two years ago while working at the 
george eastman house in rochester aber has since died but said in 
an interview at the time that she became piqued by the aesthetic 
potential of the cow when she came across an old black and white 
cow portrait from 1908 
she decided the cow merited an exhibit 
it took very quiet subtle cajoling to get it going she 
said the first response was cows why cows people would 
giggle 
but aber persisted and gathered the finest photos of cows she 
could find with some cow poetry proverbs trivia and even a cow 
video to produce her own particular ode to bovines 
theres a tremendous culture connected to the cow aber said 
thats no understatement europe the birthing ground of western 
culture is said to be named after the great white mooncow and to 
this day cows wander impoverished streets of india protected by 
an aura of sacredness 
the cows devotional heyday though probably came in ancient 
times when the animal was often thought to be the great creator 
ancient egyptians revered mother hathor as the heavenly cow 
whose udder produced the milky way whose body was the firmament 
and who daily gave birth to the sun according to barbara g walker 
in the womens encyclopedia of myths and secrets 
in old india a creation myth went that the universe was 
literally curdled into shape from milk of a great lunar cow 
some ancients in the near east believed that the human race itself 
was curdled from the goddess milk to them we are nothing but 
curds 
thus the cow was honored as a wet nurse of humanity and her 
image is still inadvertently invoked to this day as an expletive 
holy cow or a pejorative sacred cow concludes walker 
heady stuff but lately the cow has come down from the altar to 
show up in most unlikely places such items as packages of premium 
ice cream tshirts and jewelry all began sporting the stark black 
and white bovine image in the 1980s 
holy cow inc a mailorder business based in middlebury vt 
offers the usual cow shirts mugs and creamers along with more 
esoteric cow stuff such as holstein timepieces cow golf balls 
4foot high cow cut outs and even a tshirt of chairman moo one 
billion cows cant be wrong reads the catalog 
woody jacksonfounder of holy cow said his cowculture items 
including his painted cowlandscapes grossed about 15 million 
last year 
i think it makes people nostalgic said jackson trying to 
explain cow magnetism it reminds people of a simpler time plus 
everyone grows up on milk 
the exhibit itself explores the relation between man and cow 
with both humorous and more serious images an old print by lewis 
hines of a farmer and his son milking a cow is complimented by 
boris and the worlds largest cow a shot of a dog admiring a 
giant fiberglass cow 
other pictures such as rancher with her prize cattle by 
june van cleef shows just what cows can mean to people 
van cleef said her picture of a texas woman beaming proudly next 
to her animal shows how consummately important cows and cattle are 
to a whole segment of our culture 
the cattle are everything to her van cleef said 
