<TEXT>
the public concession by the federal reserve 
chairman that a credit crunch might exist confirms what a lot of 
smallbusiness people have been saying for months without getting 
much of a hearing 
the fact they didnt receive a hearing suggests something might 
be wrong with the way regulators and some important business 
institutions gather and assimilate information 
cries of distress from the smallbusiness and beginningbusiness 
sectors were at first dismissed as 
anecdotal why the explanation went everyone knows of a good 
little business that got a raw deal from the bank but dramatic as 
such stories might sound it was said the numbers didnt add up to 
a trend 
geographically limited such as to new england 
limited to industries related to building and real estate 
which already were overextended 
in response to the clamor from some small businesses that 
bankers were denying them credit the conference boards chief 
economist gail fosler observed there is no evidence of a credit 
crisis managed or otherwise 
the national federation of independent business which regularly 
surveys more than 500000 independent business members said it 
found no evidence of credit tightening nationally 
all this seemed in contradiction to the cries coming from other 
directions 
the small business association of new england asked 60 business 
people at a meeting if a crunch existed fortyeight said yes 
hardly a day passed in any area of the country larger than a few 
square miles that some smallbusiness person didnt complain about 
some sort of financial restrictions by local banks 
the national association of home builders surveyed 1142 members 
and declared that builders are being indiscriminately cut off 
from the credit markets production is dropping people are losing 
their jobs and businesses 
the fed retreated from its earlier position it surveyed some 
members banks and found more than half had tightened lending 
standards for small and mediumsize companies 
now six weeks later chairman alan greenspan says the fed is 
prepared to take modest offsetting action against a crunch 
the episode provokes questions why did it take so long to 
recognize why were the smallbusiness complaints so readily 
dismissed what is wrong with the ways business and regulators 
determine if a crunch exists 
some possibilities 
tight money is measured by what happens to the nations largest 
companies rather than to small companies or beginning companies 
evidence is statistical it does not measure banker attitudes 
in this regard it is significant that the credit crunch didnt 
originate so much with a tightmoney policy by the fed as from 
voluntary restraints by bankers some overreacting to their 
previous easylending policies 
in a sense the money was there but the banks didnt lend it 
typically many of the smaller businesses in such groups at the 
national federation of independent business rely on internal 
financing rather than on credit lines from the bank moreover they 
are established businesses 
the worst of the credit restraints seem to have affected very 
small businesses entrepreneurial ventures and businesses seeking 
to take what bankers might consider imprudent risks 
more often than some regulators statisticians academics and 
economists might like to concede national statistics often 
overlook this category the numbers they gather and analyze usually 
are bigbusiness numbers 
in defense of the tightmoney situation some observers have 
commented that it served the purpose of discouraging new and risky 
ventures such as real estate developments in areas already 
overbuilt cant quibble with that 
what some smallbusiness people feel angry and disturbed about 
however is that it is their ideas their innovations their 
dedication their risktaking that creates new enterprises new 
jobs new competition 
in short they say it is new businesses that seed economic 
change and development and it isnt fair to them or to the country 
that good ideas and good small businesses should be financially 
starved and then ignored 
