<TEXT>
wall street will try to break a jinx of sorts as 
hundreds of corporations issue midyear earnings reports over the 
next couple of weeks 
in each of the past three quarterly peak reporting periods in 
april january and last october the stock market has suffered a 
setback as profits fell short of expectations 
on the basis of the early evidence a good many earnings 
disappointments are in store again for the second quarter which 
ended june 30 but hopes have built up that the market can ride out 
the storm this time given its steady rise of late to new highs 
the situation spotlights a dichotomy that has been confronting 
market participants for almost a year now 
overall statistics on the economy have been painting a picture 
of an ideal combination of modest and noninflationary growth 
in the words of edward kerschner analyst at painewebber inc but 
corporate earnings figures project the contrasting image of a 
profit recession 
as a result kerschner says the market has been dancing a new 
threestep steady to up in the two months when the macroeconomic 
data are encouraging then falling in the month when earnings are 
reported 
only at the end of the quarter when profit reports are 
disappointing does the stock market come under pressure 
this behavior spotlights a question as old as the market itself 
what precisely is the relationship between business earnings and 
stock prices 
nobody disputes that profits are a basic building block in the 
structure of stock values since they represent the flow of money 
available for dividend payments to shareholders and for 
reinvestment in future growth 
but the correlation between the two can sometimes seem very 
tenuous this year when stocks have jumped ahead while earnings 
slumped has been one of those times 
investors have always believed that corporate earnings are a 
principal if not the key ingredient in determining the direction 
of stock prices says the investment management firm jw 
seligman amp co in a recent report on the subject 
as profits increase stock prices reflect this improvement 
when they contract prices are expected to fall while this truism 
appears quite obvious in theory unfortunately it is not clear in 
actual practice 
a check of market history over the last four decades provides a 
good illustration of this inconsistent relationship seligman 
analysts say 
there is a clear correlation between longterm earnings growth 
and stock appreciation thus the basic premise is valid over long 
time frames they observe 
but deviations from the norm can test the faith of even the most 
patient investor 
in the 1970s for example profits of the companies in standard 
amp poors industrial stock index increased 170 percent by one 
measure but the index itself gained just 56 percent over the 
decade in a market buffeted by worries about such matters as 
accelerating inflation and the energy crisis 
in a given year the divergence can be even greater 
analysts say investors must bear in mind that stock prices 
reflect expectations about future earnings more than any response 
to past results thus the current strength in the stock market 
despite earnings weakness over the last several quarters can be 
interpreted as a forecast of improved profits in the 
nottoodistant future 
seligman concludes if business continues to weaken and 
profits slide further it seems likely that the current rally will 
prove to have been a false one 
we believe however that probabilities favor market price 
action being an accurate forecasting mechanism as it has been so 
often in the past profits should improve as yeartoyear 
comparisons become more favorable in the third and fourth 
quarters 
</TEXT>
