<TEXT>
federal securities regulators are exploring 
plans for a financial warning system to head off potential troubles 
at big brokerage firms like those that sank drexel burnham lambert 
inc 
the securities and exchange commission voted thursday to seek 
public comment on proposed changes in the net capital rule 
that rule requires brokerdealers to maintain minimum amounts of 
cash and assets easily converted into cash to offset the risk of 
the securities they trade 
this is not part of a process in which the commission is 
seeking to micromanage or secondguess the management of a either 
brokerdealer or its parent sec chairman richard c breeden said 
this is more in the nature of what i would characterize as a 
smoke alarm a smoke detector he said this is more or less a 
corporate equivalent of that 
last februarys sudden collapse of the parent company of junk 
bond giant drexel has raised concerns that regulators arent 
getting enough advance notice when the parents of wall street firms 
withdraw large amounts from capital reserves 
while financially sound itself drexels brokerage business was 
a victim of money woes at its parent drexel burnham lambert group 
inc dbl group filed for bankruptcy court protection after 
defaulting on 100 million in shortterm debt the sec and the new 
york stock exchange refused to allow it to draw down cash from the 
brokerage to repay its debt 
breeden said the intent of the rule change to give us a chance 
to make a quick review of whether a sudden and really enormous in 
proportion to total capital movement of capital is due to 
something thats a planned event or due to striking an iceberg 
richard g ketchum director of the secs market regulation 
division said there are legitimate reasons like a restructuring 
for a parent company to withdraw large amounts of capital 
the rule change he said is in reaction to situations like 
drexel where the parent company was having major financing 
problems 
he and other sec officials said their task would be easier by 
pending legislation that would give them access to the financial 
health of the parent holding companies of broker dealers 
the proposed rules changes must be reviewed and possibly 
reworked before the commission can vote on fial passage 
the proposal would require brokerdealers to give the sec two 
days notice before withdrawing net capital beyond a prescribed 
amount in excess of 20 percent over a 30day period or 30 percent 
within a 90day period 
current rules do not set a time limit for firms to report 
capital problems to the sec although they must file periodic 
disclosure statements firms are required to maintain net capital 
equalling at least 5 percent of customerrelated receivables and 
below 2 percent they must cease operations 
the proposed rule change also would give the sec authority to 
stop further capital transfers if it determines the result would 
put the firm in financial jeopardy said ketchum 
in addition the change would upgrade the standard for limiting 
capital withdrawals the standard now is tied to the value of 
customer obligations 
</TEXT>
