<TEXT>
in an unusual case testing whether federal 
labor laws apply to us subsidiaries overseas a south korean 
union is suing an american manufacturer of cable television 
components for more than 1 million in back wages 
a south korean union sued pico products inc in us district 
court on thursday alleging breach of contract for shutting down 
its south korean factory and withholding more than 1 million in 
wages from workers 
an attorney for the union said the lawsuit was the first in 
federal court by foreign workers seeking to settle a labor 
disagreement 
the lawsuit accuses pico based in liverpool ny of suddenly 
closing its pico korea ltd factory in buchun city in february 1989 
to avoid compliance with a collective bargaining agreement 
the union is seeking back wages and severance it claims are owed 
to 294 workers employed by pico korea a wholly owned subsidiary of 
pico 
frank e deale legal director of the center for constitutional 
rights in new york city which is representing the south korean 
union said the lawsuit was filed on the basis of two federal laws 
they are the labor management relations act which gives federal 
courts jurisdiction to enforce collective bargaining agreements and 
the 1988 worker adjustment retraining and notification act which 
entitles all workers employed by american corporations to 60day 
notice of plant closings 
deale said the lawsuit would test whether that law can apply to 
employees of a us corporation who work abroad 
pico chairman bernard hitchcock repeated claims that union 
representatives are terrorists who kidnapped a company 
management team ransacked the factory and seized its contents and 
extorted unreasonable contract concessions 
they ripped us off for 2 million and stole the company im 
through with these people were now in court and im happy with 
that hitchcock said 
during their threemonth stay in the united states the union 
leaders and a growing number of supporters have picketed picos 
headquarters regularly 
last weekend they protested outside hitchcocks home in 
syracuse hitchcock responded by standing on his roof and dousing 
the demonstrators with water from a garden hose 
jum soon yoo president of the south korean union and a dozen 
other supporters ended a weeklong hunger strike with the filing of 
the lawsuit 
yoo and two other union leaders came to the united states in 
april to get hitchcock to negotiate a settlement after failing to 
resolve the dispute in their homeland hitchcock has refused to 
negotiate with the union 
yoo said the union brought the lawsuit because the south korean 
and american governments were ignoring the crimes of 
multinational firms against third world workers 
the union charged that pico korea took advantage of its status 
as a foreign firm and enjoyed tax breaks and other benefits offered 
by the south korean government 
the company grew rapidly after it opened in march 1983 the 
workers mobilized in june 1988 to form a union in response to what 
they called unsafe working conditions and subminimum wages 
the union and company reached a labor accord in november 1988 
that excluded the issue of wages which was to be settled through 
future talks according to the lawsuit 
but before those talks could begin hitchcock fired pico koreas 
top officers and ordered the plant shut down the lawsuit alleged 
union members admitted seizing the plant on feb 28 1989 and 
refusing to allow shipment of finished products but said they did 
so to force negotiations 
