a federal jury believed the testimony of ivan 
boesky at least in part against former stock speculator john a 
mulheren jr despite courtoom attacks on the admitted inside 
trader securities experts said 
jurors in federal court in manhattan convicted mulheren of four 
counts of conspiracy and stock manipulation stemming from dealings 
with boesky in 1985 but failed to reached a verdict on 26 other 
counts 
us district judge miriam goldman cedarbaum dismissed the panel 
and declared a mistrial on the undecided charges thursday after 
nine days of deliberations failed to yield a verdict 
the conviction of the flamboyant mulheren on the four counts 
returned tuesday marked another victory for the government 
juries have returned guilty verdicts against the principal 
defendants in all but one of about a dozen cases in prosecutors 
fouryear crackdown on wall street fraud many defendants have 
pleaded guilty rather than face trial 
mulherens conviction also followed another pattern securities 
experts said in that the jury convicted on charges that contained 
a clear victim of fraud in this case involving the manipulation of 
gulf amp western inc stock 
they appeared stymied however on more technical allegations of 
stock parking a violation that before the recent wave of cases 
typically was prosecuted as a civil rather than criminal violation 
prosecutors had charged mulheren bought 75000 gulf amp western 
shares at boeskys behest driving the stock to 45 a share the 
price at which boesky wanted to sell about 35 million shares back 
to the company 
the jury was hung up on charges that mulheren secretly held 
large blocks of stock to help boesky evade taxes and federal 
securities disclosure laws 
the jury obviously believed boesky on the most central 
transaction said john c coffee jr a securities law professor 
at columbia university 
they convicted on on the story that had the clearest motive 
and clearest sense of injury coffee said gulf and western you 
can understand there is a victim there who has been defrauded 
the company paid too much 
stock parking is more of a regulatory crime he said 
parking refers to the illegal practice of disguising ownership of 
securities to avoid federal reporting requirements 
mulheren 41 was an aggressive and successful trader of stocks 
of companies targeted for takeover before he was implicated in 1988 
in the governments fraud investigation by boesky a former friend 
and associate 
