not be the role of the fcc that should be the role of parents 
currently obscene material is banned from the airwaves at all 
times and indecent material from about 6 am to 8 pm 
the fcc defines indecent as language or material that depicts 
or describes in terms patently offensive as measured by 
contemporary community standards for the broadcast medium sexual 
or excretory activities or organs 
the fcc under its new chairman alfred sikes has in the past 
year put the nations radio stations on notice it will not tolerate 
the broadcast of indecent programs before 8 pm it has fined 
several stations already for broadcasting sexually explicit 
material 
sikes said thursday that in seeking a 24hour ban the fcc 
simply was reflecting the will of congress and the american public 
weve received a huge amount of mail and it seems the 
public strongly supports the action were taking today he said 
fcc officials repeatedly refused to speculate on what types of 
tv programs could be considered indecent the commission in june 
1988 fined a kansas city mo tv station 2000 for showing an 
allegedly indecent film private lessons at 8 pm at that 
time the fcc had established an aftermidnight safe harbor for 
indecent programs 
however the fcc vacated the fine when the appeals court in july 
1988 ordered the commission to study the timeofday issue further 
in its report the fcc said a 24hour indecency ban promotes a 
compelling government interest and was narrowly tailored to 
serve that interest without infringing broadcasters first 
amendment rights 
the commission said it was guided by a 1989 supreme court ruling 
that used the compelling interestnarrowly tailored argument in 
deciding that the government had the right to regulate indecent 
telephone transmissions 
congress in 1988 ordered the fcc to adopt a roundtheclock ban 
on indecency and it did but broadcasters and freespeech groups 
challenged the rules and the us court of appeals for the 
district of columbia in january 1989 stayed implementation of the 
24hour ban pending further review 
the court said the fcc could develop evidence supporting a 
24hour ban 
