<TEXT>
consumer advocates and industry officials 
agree shoppers would find it easier to learn the nutrition content 
of nearly all foods in the grocery store under a new government 
proposal to overhaul food labeling 
shoppers would be able to tell at a glance the amount of 
saturted fat calories from fat cholesterol and fiber serving 
sizes would be standardized so nutrient comparisons would be more 
meaningful 
but this doesnt assure the proposals smooth sailing among the 
public or within the bush administration 
its a step in the right direction but its a long road and 
the question isnt what theyre proposing but whether theyll ever 
finalize it said ellen haas executive director of the consumer 
group public voice for food amp health policy 
past efforts by the food and drug administration to change the 
foodlabeling system stalled which prompted action in congress 
rep henry waxman dcalif and sen howard metzenbaum dohio 
are sponsoring bills that would accomplish many of the same things 
the regulation would 
on thursday health and human services secretary louis sullivan 
outlined the latest effort to make sweeping changes in the system 
to be published in 400 pages of the federal register next week 
the proposals would 
require nutrition labeling for most packaged foods as well as 
fresh produce and seafood 
require labels to include saturated fat calories from fat 
cholesterol and fiber 
establish standardized serving sizes for 159 food categories 
restrict use of the terms no cholesterol low 
cholesterol and reduced cholesterol 
food industry representatives applauded the effort and said 
they will continue pressing to have the regulations applied 
uniformly nationwide 
the issue held up announcement of the regulations late last 
month because of a disagreement within the administration 
according to sources who spoke on condition of anonymity 
the health and human services department wanted uniform rules 
but white house reportedly officials objected saying states should 
be allowed to build their own regulations onto the federal ones 
to get the proposed regulations published and begin the 
administrative rulemaking process the uniformity language was 
stripped from the proposal and the issue instead was posed as a 
question for comment 
without uniform labeling there will be consumer confusion and 
distribution chaos said c manly molpus president of the 
grocery manufacturers of america 
under the proposed regulation nutrition labels would have to 
appear on product packages for fresh produce and seafood 
nutrition information could be available at the point of purchase 
such as in brochures or on posters 
listing of the thiamin riboflavin and niacin now required 
would become optional and listing of protein would be required 
only for food intended for infants and very young children 
to be called cholesterol free a product would have to have 
less than two grams of saturated fat less than five grams of total 
fat and less than two milligrams of cholesterol a food meeting the 
targets on fat but with two to 20 milligrams of cholesterol could 
be called low cholesterol 
a manufacturer could claim a food had reduced cholesterol if 
its cholesterol was cut by at least 75 percent it could also make 
that claim if the reduction was compared with other foods on the 
market but the comparison would have to be explained on the label 
the axiom here is truth in labeling said acting fda 
commissioner james benson 
hhs set a 30day comment period on the cholesterol rule and said 
it could become final by the fall manufacturers would then have 
one year to comply 
a 120day comment period was set for the regulations on 
nutritional labeling intake references and serving size benson 
said he hoped a final regulation could be issued by next spring 
the industry would have a year to comply 
exemptions to the labeling rule would include restaurants 
bakeries cafeterias bitesize foods and foods that have less than 
40 calories per serving do not make a health claim and have no 
meaningful supply of nutrients 
