<DOCNO> AP900713-0233 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
for the bond market this years second quarter 
turned out to be an unwelcome rerun of the first 
the bond investors association a nonprofit group that tracks 
bond defaults says 26 us corporations stopped making interest 
payments on bonds with a face value of 57 billion in the 
apriljune period 
that compares with 14 issuers who defaulted on an identical 
amount of bonds in the first quarter 
the default rate is almost twice the historic rate said 
richard lehmann president of the groupwe think thats basically 
because the quality of the debt that was put out from 85 to 89 
was vastly inferior to what was done before 
lehmann places the blame on junk bonds those highrisk 
highyield debt securities that were the rage during the takeover 
binge of the mid to late 1980s 
the junk bond market has all but dried up due to the demise 
earlier this year of drexel burnham lambert the wall street house 
that built its shortlived fortune by selling and tirelessly 
promoting junk issues 
but the junk bonds it pumped out in the 80s are coming home to 
roost or die as seems to be more the case all of the defaulted 
bonds in the second quarter were junk issues lehmann says 
among them were 19 billion in bonds sold by southland corp 
troubled owner of the 7eleven chain 652 million in bonds issued 
by equally troubled fellow convenience store operator circle k 
corp 705 million in bonds sold by farley inc for its 
underfunded takeover of textile giant west pointpepperell and 
637 million in western union corp bonds all were drexel clients 
also among major bond defaulters in the second quarter were 
troubled savings and loans which had issued junk as a lastditch 
attempt to stave off collapse 
among them were imperial corp of america a san diego thrift 
holding company with 342 million in bad bonds and centrust bank 
of miami at 315 million the bond investors association says 
lehmann said he doesnt expect bond defaults to ease anytime 
soon over the next three years he projects a total of 40 billion 
in corporate bond issues will stop making payments 
it should peak early next year and then start to decline but 
if the economy turns bad it could go on through next year he 
said last week in a telephone interview from his groups suburban 
miami headquarters 
had drexel survived and the junk market not collapsed many of 
these troubled junkfinanced deals from the past few years might 
have been able to restructure their debt and avoid default said 
david blitzer chief economist for standard amp poors corp a major 
credit rating agency 
drexels destruction left many junkdependent clients in the 
cold they found themselves without a link to the market 
blitzer said 
these companies also found closed doors elsewhere he said as 
banks became wary of highly leveraged deals when the real estate 
market soured and credit tightened 
lehmanns group said only 12 new junk bond issues totaling 17 
billion were sold in the second quarter compared with 93 issues 
totaling 156 billion in 1989s second quarter 
recently however some experts have said the junk bond market 
may not be all gloom and doom 
junk bonds have staged a rally of sorts in recent months and by 
some measures some of the bonds have provided better returns to 
investors than some investmentgrade issues 
the market received a boost last month when kohlberg kravis 
roberts amp co the big new york investment group said it would 
inject 17 billion into rjr nabisco the food and tobacco company 
it took private last year 
the news ended speculation that rjr could become another 
troubled junk bond giant 
