daimlerbenz honda toyota nissan and more than 20 other 
companies the ford case was the first to go to trial 
dennis kearns said other automakers also being sued by his 
father probably would offer minuscule settlements in light of 
the ford verdict 
kearns 63 originally sought 141 million an amount that could 
have been tripled had the previous damages trial determined that 
ford willfully infringed on kearns patents 
ford attorneys said a reasonable licensing agreement would have 
paid the inventor 15 million or less 
the jurys award for 63 million was based on what kearns had 
called fords profit of 685 on each of 206 million 
intermittentwiper options it sold from 19721988 when his main 
patents were in effect 
during a friday afternoon hearing us district judge avern 
cohn ordered the award reduced to 516 million which represents 
what is owed to kearns only after april 1978 when he originally 
filed suit 
the jury that decided kearns patents had been infringed 
deadlocked on how much money he should get the second jury heard 
evidence pertaining only to the damages kearns suffered through the 
infringement 
</TEXT>
